Want to join Big Orange Boosters?
Everyone is welcome! No requirement to have kids in school.

2019-2020 was a great year for Big Orange Boosters. We will be able to make a very nice donation back to USD 214 Activities at our first Home Football game.

A 2020-2021 Membership Form is attached. Feel free to print and return this form to join in on the fun this year. They can be mailed to us or dropped off at the Booster Booth on Friday, September 18th at the Scrimmages being held at UHS and Maxwell Field. Membership forms need to be received no later than Sept 16th to be included in the Homecoming Insert.

Also, check out our FaceBook page to see any new and upcoming items or events.

Big Orange Boosters
PO Box441
Ulysses, KS

shared_text:
Justin Coffey
August 5 at 9:11 PM ·

Educating our kids is not political. It is not a Republican issue or a Democrat issue. It’s an American issue. I understand that we are living in an incredibly divisive time. But, how amazing would it be if we all rallied together to support the education of our children? If we all worked together to make things both as normal as possible and as safe as possible at the same time? We’re going to have to make some compromises to make it all work. It is CERTAINLY not ideal. No one likes the situation we find ourselves in. But, for our kids, let’s come together and make the best of a very tough situation.

Also, if you know someone in education, please give them some grace for a month or two. August is always a stressful and anxious time for educators, but this August the stress and anxiety is off the charts. Please know they are working to both make things as normal as possible and make things as safe as possible in our schools.

****Even if you have done it before, please!!

Your coaches are all excited to get going and we are looking forward to camp and to the season which we will start on August 17th. Practices for season will be at 4pm.

Let’s go Lady Tigers!!

UHS Graduation 2020
Saturday, June 27th at 9:00am at Maxwell Field (football field)

Graduates will be limited to bringing 6 guests each in order to promote social distancing. Guests will be asked to seat themselves in the home grandstands or track with 6ft distancing between family units. There will also be limited seating behind the stage on the football field but guests will need to provide their own blanket or seating for this. The commencement stage will be set up on the track on the west side of the field with the graduates seated on the track directly in front of the stage. The stage will face the home grandstands.

The entire graduation ceremony will be streamed live on the UHS YouTube channel.
The direct link to access the ceremony will be posted out as the graduation ceremony nears.

* Seniors, there will be a letter mailed to you directly with the information packet for the ceremony and tickets.

UHS Student/Athletes:
Monday, June 1st at 6:00 a.m. there will be a meeting at the Game football field for all high school boys planning on participating in a sport for the 2020-2021 seasons. At 7:00 a.m. there will be a meeting at the Game Football field for all high school girls planning on participating in a sport for the 2020-2021 seasons. Please, make an effort to attend. Even if you do not plan on playing sports, you are welcome to attend this meeting and be part of the summer weight/conditioning program.
KSHSAA has made it mandatory that each athlete participates in 10 days of weights/conditioning before being able to participate in team sports this summer.
This meeting is extremely important for the preparation of a summer lifting/conditioning schedule and guidelines that MUST be followed during these times.
We look forward to seeing you all on Monday. Let’s prepare for a great sports year.

post_text:
May 22, 2020



KSHSAA Member School Principals & Athletic/Activity Directors:

All student-athletes are required to get a new PPE for the 2020-21 school year.

The KSHSAA Sports Medicine Advisory Committee met on May 20 to consider potential modification of requirements of the annual Preparticipation Physical Exam. Following extended discussion, a review of literature, and a geographic check of each represented area relative to local health care access, the committee supported a motion to maintain the current practice and require “new” PPE’s for every athletic and spirit participant. Accordingly, the KSHSAA will not request the BOD to consider further action in this regard and Rule 7-Physical Examination Parental Consent will not be modified.
text:
May 22, 2020



KSHSAA Member School Principals & Athletic/Activity Directors:

All student-athletes are required to get a new PPE for the 2020-21 school year.

The KSHSAA Sports Medicine Advisory Committee met on May 20 to consider potential modification of requirements of the annual Preparticipation Physical Exam. Following extended discussion, a review of literature, and a geographic check of each represented area relative to local health care access, the committee supported a motion to maintain the current practice and require “new” PPE’s for every athletic and spirit participant. Accordingly, the KSHSAA will not request the BOD to consider further action in this regard and Rule 7-Physical Examination Parental Consent will not be modified.

shared_text:
Justin Coffey
May 18 at 8:01 PM ·

Seniors, this school year didn’t end the way we would have liked. But, let me be real with you for a moment. This is exactly how life goes. Life is not fair. Life can be difficult at times. Life is full of adversity. When life is difficult, it’s easy to mope and feel sorry for yourself (sometimes you have to mope and feel sorry for yourself for a day or two). The secret to living a great life is the way you act when life knocks you down. Your life will be exponentially improved if you express gratitude for the blessings in your life and if you find ways to serve and give to others. When you do this, it not only brighten someone else’s day, it also makes you feel better. That. Is. How. You. Change. The. World.

Seniors, here’s your chance. Let’s make something great out of a tough situation. Let’s change the world. I look forward to seeing your action!

In addition to the #KSClassof2020 hashtag, please use the #UHSClassof2020 hashtag so I can see your greatness!!

E + R = O

Attention UHS seniors:

On Thursday, May 14, we will have Chromebook check-in at UHS as well as normal checkout procedures where you must turn in all textbooks, library books, pay fees, and turn in any other items that must be returned to the school.

Anytime during the times of 8:30am-11:30am, seniors with last name A-M, need to come to school and checkout.

Anytime from 1:00pm-4:00pm seniors with last name N-Z, need to come to school and checkout.

If you have a conflict and must come in the morning or afternoon opposite your scheduled last name, that will be allowed.

We will observe social distancing and only allow 10 people or less to congregate in the building at a time, so feel free to stagger your arrival.

For any questions about this, call the UHS office at 356-1380 during business hours of 8:00am - 4:00pm or email, mpaul@ulysses.org

College Admissions Resource Document



We know during this time of uncertainty many senior students and families may have a lot of questions and concerns regarding post-secondary plans. The Kansas Board of Regents (KBOR) and Kansas State Department of Education (KSDE) are working together to develop resources to provide information to alleviate some of these concerns and answer important questions.

We developed a College Admissions Among COVID-19 document that provides helpful admissions and financial aid links and virtual tools from Kansas public and independent institutions, as well as college and career exploration tools and articles related to college-decision making for 2020 graduates. We hope that you find this resource helpful. The link will auto-update as additional information is added.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1UbIxkS9dhZBd1lXpvB1MoZwLBlAGPty5/view

Here are some resources from the UHS counseling department that address talking about the Coronavirus with your child as well as a variety of social emotional resources related to COVID-19. Calm is also a free app that students can download for meditation, relaxation, and stress relief. Our school counselors are available by e-mail (Mrs. Reimer-hreimer@ulysses.org & Mrs. Darrough-Hayden (kdarrough-hayden@ulysses.org) as well as by arranged virtual meetings. Remember that Compass Behavioral Health (620-356-3198) is also a resource if needed during this time.



https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/talking-with-children.html

If this applies to you, Mexico included, over Spring Break, please do not come to the school. Arrangements, at a later date, can be made.

Parents/students need to be aware that they should not enter the building or be in public if:
They have traveled to a foreign country since March 15.
If parents/students traveled to Pitkin, Eagle, Summit, or Gunnison counties in Colorado since March 8.
If they have traveled to California, Florida, New York, Washington State, New Jersey or Illinois since March 15.
If anyone entering the building is sick.

Students will be allowed to enter the school building to pick up any personal items they need from lockers, etc. on Thursday and Friday this week. In order to comply with social distancing recommendations, we will use the following schedule:

Freshmen - Thursday, March 26 from 8:00-11:00am
Sophomores - Thursday, March 26 from 12:00-3:00pm
Juniors - Friday, March 27 from 8:00-11:00am
Seniors - Friday, March 27 from 12:00-3:00pm

Please check-in through the front office as only 10 students will be allowed in the school at a time.

If you miss this time period and are needing to pick up your personal items please call the UHS office at 620-356-1380 to make an appointment.

Ulysses Public Schools
March 15 at 5:23 PM ·

We are in unprecedented times in dealing with the Covid 19 virus The district is relying on local, state, and federal health officials to help make many critical decisions that affect our students, staff, and our communities.

Based on a webinar today we have cancelled Spring sports practices this week.

We will continue to meet with the health and educational leaders and hope to have more information of "what's next" available by midweek.

Thank you for your patience and understanding in this difficult time.

UHS wants to thank all students, parents, and teachers who made the time to partner up in the process of Parent-Teacher Conferences. I feel this increased communication between students, parents, and teachers is a valuable part of a successful educational process.

Conferences do not need to take place only on designated conference dates. Feel free to call the UHS office (620-356-1380) at any time to set up a meeting with teachers and administration to help with any concerns you might have.

Also, feel free to contact UHS Principal Mr Paul with any suggestions you may have to improve the current PT Conference process.

post_text:
Interesting facts from the February 2020 KSHSAA Journal that support what most of us already know, but is a good reminder of the positive impact athletics has at our high school:

95 percent of Fortune 500 executives in 1987 participated in school athletics (only 47 percent were National Honor Society members). - FORTUNE MAGAZINE

By a 2 to 1 margin for males and a 3 to 1 margin for females, student-athletes do better in school, do not drop out and have a better chance to get through college.

Nearly 7 in 10 Americans say high school sports teach students lessons about life they can’t learn in a classroom; 9 in 10 believe sports contribute to health and fitness.

High school athletes have higher grades and lower dropout rates and attend college more than nonathletes.

As coaches, we would do well to remember the positive impact our sport is having on our players - even if sometimes the Wins are not what we would like.

Kim Darrough-Hayden and Heather Reimer, thank you for all you do for us at UHS!

TOPEKA — National School Counseling Week, which takes places Monday, Feb. 3, through Friday, Feb. 7, highlights the tremendous impact the nearly 1,300 licensed public school counselors in Kansas have in helping students achieve success.

More than 100,000 school counselors across the country, including 1,299 licensed public school counselors in Kansas, will be participating in the week’s festivities.

The American School Counselor Association (ASCA) sponsors the week.

School counselors provide students with academic, college and career help and social-emotional development.

The theme for this year’s celebration is “School Counselors: Helping Build Better Humans.”

shared_text:
Adelaide Harrold
January 20 at 1:14 PM ·

Every year the seniors are required to do a project that serves the community. My project was setting up a “school closet” so that high school kids in need of clothes, can come and get some for free. With lots of help from Jennifer Moyer Hegwood, the community, my peers, and teachers, I was finally able to get it up and running. We have lots of nice clothes that students can use for interviews, church, etc. We also have casual clothes for kids to wear around the house and to school. On top of that we have also had lots of soaps, and towels donated to us so that kids who don’t have access to showers at home can use the ones in the locker rooms if needed. If students are interested is obtaining some clothes, they can ask any teacher or administrator at the high school that they trust to unlock the closets for them and help them find their size.
If you’d like to donate any of your slightly used clothes, towels, or toiletries just take them to the UHS office. I am thrilled to have this project up and running, and to be able to give back to a community that has done so much for me.

post_text: The Ulysses Odyssey of the Mind teams have extra tea and coffee products left to sell. Everything is $10 each. We have Coffee in both bags and K-Cups and Tea. Flavors of Coffee include: Caramel Mudslide, Breakfast Blend, Hazelnut, House Blend, Yankee Doodle, and Southern Pecan. Tea flavors include: Mango, Orange Spice, Peach Apricot, Earl Grey, Black Currant, and Raspberry. Please contact Misti Hamilton-Becker at the high school if you would like anything before the holidays.
